With the growing world of web, there are numerous use-cases which require tasks to be executed in an asynchronous manner and in a distributed fashion. 
Celery is one of the most robust, scalable, extendable and easy-to-implement frameworks available for distributed task processing. While developing applications using Celery, I have had considerable experience in terms of what design choices one should be aware of while evaluating an existing system or developing one's own system from scratch.</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Konark Modi</dc:creator><pubDate>Wed, 23 Jul 2014 00:00:00 -0500</pubDate><guid>http://www.pyvideo.org/video/3007/design-considerations-while-evaluating-developin</guid><enclosure url="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zdk3IoLnjMg" length="None" type="video/flv"></enclosure><media:thumbnail url="http://i.ytimg.com/vi/zdk3IoLnjMg/hqdefault.jpg"></media:thumbnail></item><item><title>Designing NRT(NearRealTime) stream processing systems: using python with Storm and Kafka</title><link>http://www.pyvideo.org/video/3016/designing-nrtnearrealtime-stream-processing-sys</link><description>&lt;p&gt;Abstract&lt;/p&gt;
The essence of near-real-time stream processing is to compute huge volumes of data as it is received. This talk will focus on creating a pipeline for collecting huge volumes of data using Kafka and processing for near-real time computations using Storm.</description><dc:creator xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/">Konark Modi</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 22 Jul 2014 00:00:00 -0500</pubDate><guid>http://www.pyvideo.org/video/3016/designing-nrtnearrealtime-stream-processing-sys</guid><enclosure url="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwiHZru2Wjc" length="None" type="video/flv"></enclosure><media:thumbnail url="http://i.ytimg.com/vi/uwiHZru2Wjc/hqdefault.jpg"></media:thumbnail></item></channel></rss>